NODE_1_length_685731_cov_56.949454	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	261600	261974	.	+	0	ID=MGA_228;product=hypothetical protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator;translation=MIGPRPVVEEELAAYGDDAGELLSAKPGITGWWQVQARNDATYGDGSRQELELSRGGVSGAPRRFAQPLRGEGLPAPRLAGASGTSRRLAAPPAPRTPVSSIPTASMWIYRAIASIVKVLLATS;locus_tag=LOCUS_02270;note=WP_004538719.1 sugar transferase (Burkholderia) [pid:57.4%25%2C q_cov:43.5%25%2C s_cov:14.6%25%2C Eval:6.1e-11%2C partial hit],TIGR:TIGR03022%3B WbaP_sugtrans: undecaprenyl-phosphate galactose phosphotransferase WbaP [Name:TIGR03022%2C Eval:2.6e-14%2C score:51.3%2C bias:0.0],Domain:cl27431:Bac_transf Bacterial sugar transferase. Members of this family are generally found near other genes involved in the biosynthesis of a variety of exopolysaccharides. These proteins consist of two fused domains%2C an N-terminal hydrophobic domain of generally low conservation and a highly conserved C-terminal sugar transferase domain (pfam02397). Characterized and partially characterized members of this subfamily include Salmonella WbaP (originally RfbP)%2C E. coli WcaJ%2C Methylobacillus EpsB%2C Xanthomonas GumD%2C Vibrio CpsA%2C Erwinia AmsG%2C Group B Streptococcus CpsE (originally CpsD)%2C and Streptococcus suis Cps2E. Each of these is believed to act in transferring the sugar from%2C for instance%2C UDP-glucose or UDP-galactose%2C to a lipid carrier such as undecaprenyl phosphate as the first (priming) step in the synthesis of an oligosaccharide 'block'. This function is encoded in the C-terminal domain. The liposaccharide is believed to be subsequently transferred through a 'flippase' function from the cytoplasmic to the periplasmic face of the inner membrane by the N-terminal domain. Certain closely related transferase enzymes%2C such as Sinorhizobium ExoY and Lactococcus EpsD%2C lack the N-terminal domain and are not found by this model. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:1-42%2C Eval:3.4e-10%2C score:52.6%2C N-term missing],MGA_228
