NODE_4_length_348023_cov_64.420950	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	215000	215773	.	-	0	ID=MGA_1596;product=hypothetical protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator;translation=MTSGFDAFSLGLFTSLAPAGVVAFLALALVRLWSRDRTASVRIDRMIALPFSVVLIGFIASATHLGTPANALHVFSGVGRSPLSNEVLSAVAFLFLVGSYWMMAFKERFPDAVAKPWLALACLAGIALIACTSMAYNVDTVPTWDTAFTPANLVLAALLAGPVLGLLFLELAQVRPRALERARCWQALCWGSCSWSWRRCGRARSSARSSYWRRPRSWRGPSCSHCTRRAFPPSRTTSSQPARSRLPILLSSARISS;locus_tag=LOCUS_15890;note=WP_002209429.1 dimethyl sulfoxide reductase anchor subunit (Yersinia pseudotuberculosis complex) [pid:32.2%25%2C q_cov:69.6%25%2C s_cov:62.9%25%2C Eval:1.3e-24%2C partial hit],frameshifted%2C insertion/deletion at around 215251,Domain:cl21513:NrfD Polysulphide reductase%2C NrfD. Bacterial polysulfide reductase is an integral membrane protein complex responsible for quinone-coupled reduction of polysulfide%2C a process important in extreme environments such as deep-sea vents and hot springs. Polysulfides are a class of compounds composed of chains of sulfur atoms%2C which in their simplest form are present as an anion with general formula Sn(2-). In nature%2C polysulfides are found in particularly high concentrations in extreme volcanic or geothermically active environments. Here%2C the reduction and oxidation of polysulfides are vital processes for many bacteria and are essential steps in the global sulfur cycle. In particular%2C the reduction of polysulfide to hydrogen sulfide in these environments is usually linked to energy-generating respiratory processes%2C supporting growth of many microorganisms%2C particularly hyperthermophiles. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:7-179%2C Eval:2.2e-28%2C score:106.6%2C C-term missing],MGA_1596
