NODE_7_length_163110_cov_60.318126	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	22351	23166	.	-	0	ID=MGA_2108;product=hypothetical protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator;translation=MTIQWSLVLFTVLSGCGAGLFACTALDEFRGGAASKVRLPACAVAVALLVVGGIASATHLSHVDRMMAVLAHPTAGIFLEALLLGLLAVCIAVYALLVKREASSGARKALAATGIVLAVAFAFACGVSYMMTSRPVWNTVALPLAYLGTALATGAALYLVMCAALKVDEGDVKKAGVYAAAGGALSLVLTVAFGLVSGTAFGDQAALFWVAVVLCGSAAPAVCGVLVARKSGGALSLGVVALAGALVGSVAVRAVMWLVGTAVANYFGFAL;locus_tag=LOCUS_21000;note=Domain:cl21513:NrfD Polysulphide reductase%2C NrfD. Bacterial polysulfide reductase is an integral membrane protein complex responsible for quinone-coupled reduction of polysulfide%2C a process important in extreme environments such as deep-sea vents and hot springs. Polysulfides are a class of compounds composed of chains of sulfur atoms%2C which in their simplest form are present as an anion with general formula Sn(2-). In nature%2C polysulfides are found in particularly high concentrations in extreme volcanic or geothermically active environments. Here%2C the reduction and oxidation of polysulfides are vital processes for many bacteria and are essential steps in the global sulfur cycle. In particular%2C the reduction of polysulfide to hydrogen sulfide in these environments is usually linked to energy-generating respiratory processes%2C supporting growth of many microorganisms%2C particularly hyperthermophiles. [Superfamily%2C Aligned:5-157%2C Eval:3.7e-08%2C score:50.4%2C C-term missing],MGA_2108
