NODE_9_length_104966_cov_34.388201	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	13178	14395	.	-	0	ID=MGA_2393;product=ATP-grasp domain-containing protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator,similar to AA sequence:RefSeq:WP_011108800.1;;locus_tag=LOCUS_23830;note=WP_011108800.1 ATP-grasp domain-containing protein (Bacteroides thetaiotaomicron) [pid:29.2%25%2C q_cov:98.0%25%2C s_cov:100.0%25%2C Eval:1.4e-48],Domain:cl27719:Biotin_carb_N Biotin carboxylase%2C N-terminal domain. Carbamoyl-phosphate synthase (CPSase) catalyzes the first committed step in pyrimidine%2C arginine%2C and urea biosynthesis. In general%2C it is a glutamine-dependent enzyme%2C EC 6.3.5.5%2C termed CPSase II in eukaryotes. An exception is the mammalian mitochondrial urea-cycle form%2C CPSase I%2C in which the glutamine amidotransferase domain active site Cys on the small subunit has been lost%2C and the enzyme is ammonia-dependent. In both CPSase I and the closely related%2C glutamine-dependent CPSase III (allosterically activated by acetyl-glutamate) demonstrated in some other vertebrates%2C the small and large chain regions are fused in a single polypeptide chain. This model represents the large chain of glutamine-hydrolysing carbamoyl-phosphate synthases%2C or the corresponding regions of larger%2C multifunctional proteins%2C as found in all domains of life%2C and CPSase I forms are considered exceptions within the family. In several thermophilic species (Methanobacterium thermoautotrophicum%2C Methanococcus jannaschii%2C Aquifex aeolicus)%2C the large subunit appears split%2C at different points%2C into two separate genes. [Purines%2C pyrimidines%2C nucleosides%2C and nucleotides%2C Pyrimidine ribonucleotide biosynthesis] [Superfamily%2C Aligned:20-314%2C Eval:4.8e-26%2C score:106.2%2C C-term missing],MGA_2393
