NODE_11_length_84259_cov_43.597812	MetaGeneAnnotator	CDS	72163	72306	.	-	0	ID=MGA_2634;product=hypothetical protein;inference=COORDINATES:ab initio prediction:MetaGeneAnnotator;translation=MNLYITNEYTFRRVLDLYLLAWEEGVKTIYYVRSKSLEVEECEVCSS;locus_tag=LOCUS_26210;note=WP_005788368.1 ribonucleoside-diphosphate reductase subunit alpha (Bacteroides fragilis) [pid:83.8%25%2C q_cov:78.7%25%2C s_cov:4.4%25%2C Eval:9.6e-12%2C partial hit],frameshifted%2C insertion/deletion at around 72359,TIGR:TIGR02506%3B NrdE_NrdA: ribonucleoside-diphosphate reductase%2C alpha subunit [Name:TIGR02506%2C Eval:5.5e-09%2C score:32.9%2C bias:0.8],Domain:cl27341:Ribonuc_red_lgC Ribonucleotide reductase%2C barrel domain. This model represents the alpha (large) chain of the class I ribonucleotide reductase (RNR). RNR's are responsible for the conversion of the ribose sugar of RNA into the deoxyribose sugar of DNA. This is the rate-limiting step of DNA biosynthesis. Class I RNR's generate the required radical (on tyrosine) via a 'non-heme' iron cofactor which resides in the beta (small) subunit. The alpha subunit contains the catalytic and allosteric regulatory sites. The mechanism of this enzyme requires molecular oxygen. E. Coli contains two versions of this enzyme which are regulated independently (NrdAB and NrdEF%2C where NrdA and NrdE are the large chains). Most organisms contain only one%2C but the application of the gene symbols NrdA and NrdE are somewhat arbitrary. This model identifies RNR's in diverse clades of bacteria%2C eukaryotes as well as numerous DNA viruses and phage. [Purines%2C pyrimidines%2C nucleosides%2C and nucleotides%2C 2'-Deoxyribonucleotide metabolism] [Superfamily%2C Aligned:1-46%2C Eval:4.4e-12%2C score:55.1%2C N-term missing],MGA_2634
